pngd.html.body:
PNGD
The PNGD module is used to hardware decode images in PNG format.

The PNGD supports the following input formats:
RGBA and RGB

The PNGD supports the following output formats:
RGBA and RGB

The PNGD supports the following resolutions:
Maximum resolution: 4096 x 4096; minimum resolution: 32 x 32

Memory limit:

The start address of the cache must be 128-byte aligned.
The virtual addresses of the input and output caches for the same task should be in the same 4 GB space.



The performance specifications of the PNGD are as follows:

Scene

Total Frame Rate



1080p x 1 channel

4 fps


1080p x 2 channels

8 fps


1080p x 3 channels

12 fps


1080p x 4 channels

16 fps


1080p x 5 channels

20 fps


1080p ≥ 6 channels (no limit on the number of channels)

24 fps


4K x 1 channel

1 fps


4K x 2 channels

2 fps


4K x 3 channels

3 fps


4K x 4 channels

4 fps


4K x 5 channels

5 fps


4K ≥ 6 channels (no limit on the number of channels)

6 fps





Input Parameter: struct PngInputInfoAPI

Member Variable

Description



void* inputData

Input image data


unsigned long inputSize

Input buffer length, which is used to verify the input data


void* address

Buffer address, which is internally allocated and does not need to be configured by users


unsigned long size

Buffer size, which does not need to be configured by users


int transformFlag

Conversion flag. The value 1 indicates that RGBA is converted into RGB, while the value 0 indicates that the original format is retained.





Output Parameter: struct PngOutputInfoAPI

Member Variable

Description



void* outputData

Output image data


unsigned long outputSize

Output buffer length


void* address

Output buffer address, which needs to be manually released by users


unsigned long size

Buffer size


int format

Output image format
2: RGB output6: RGBA output


unsigned int width

Output image width


unsigned int high

Output image height


unsigned int widthAlign

Width alignment. The size of the buffer occupied by each line of data is 128-byte aligned. If the output format is RGB, the result of Width x 3 is 128-byte aligned. If the output format is RGBA, the result of Width x 4 is 128-byte aligned.


unsigned int highAlign

Height alignment. Currently, 16-byte alignment is used.





Calling Example
int test() // Basic test case of the PNGD
{
 // load test file
 FILE *fpIn = fopen("dvpp_png_decode_001", "rb");
 if(NULL == fpIn){
  printf("can not open file dvpp_png_decode_001\n");
  return -1;
 }
 fseek(fpIn, 0, SEEK_END);
 uint32_t fileLen = ftell(fpIn);
 fseek(fpIn, 0, SEEK_SET);
 void* inbuf = malloc(fileLen);
 if(NULL == inbuf){
  printf("can not alloc memmory\n");
  fclose(fpIn);
  return -1;
 }else{
     fread(inbuf, 1, fileLen, fpIn);
 }
 fclose(fpIn);
 // prepare msg
        struct PngInputInfoAPI inputInfo; // Input data
        inputInfo.inputData = inbuf; // Input PNG data
        inputInfo.inoutSize = fileLen; // Length of the input PNG data
       inputInfo.transformFlag = 0; // Whether to convert the format
        struct PngOutputInfoAPI outputInfo; // Output data
       dvppapi_ctl_msg dvppApiCtlMsg; //: MSG for the calling API
    dvppApiCtlMsg.in       = (void*)(&inputInfo);
    dvppApiCtlMsg.in_size  = sizeof(struct PngInputInfoAPI);
    dvppApiCtlMsg.out      = (void*)(&outputInfo);
    dvppApiCtlMsg.out_size = sizeof(struct PngOutputInfoAPI);
    // use interface
    IDVPPAPI *pidvppapi = NULL;
       CreateDvppApi(pidvppapi); // Crearte a DVPP API object.
        if(pidvppapi){// Call the DvppCtl interface to perform DVPP_CTL_PNGD_PROC.
    if(0 != DvppCtl(pidvppapi, DVPP_CTL_PNGD_PROC, &dvppApiCtlMsg)){
        printf("call dvppctl process failed\n");
                DestroyDvppApi(pidvppapi); // Destroy the DVPP API object.
        return -1;
    }
    }else{
        printf("can not get dvpp api\n");
    }
    free(inbuf);
    munmap(outputInfo.address, ALIGN_UP(outputInfo.size, MAP_2M));
    DestroyDvppApi(pidvppapi);
}

venc.html.body:
VENC
Function
The VENC module is used to encode YUV420/YVU420 image data.

The VENC supports the following input formats:
YUV420 semi-planar NV12/NV21 8-bit

The VENC supports the following output formats:
H.264 BP/MP/HP
H.265 MP


The performance specifications of the VENC are as follows:

Scene

Total Frame Rate



1080p x 1 channel (multiple channels are not supported)

30 fps





Input Parameter: venc_in_msg

Member Variable

Description

Value Range



Int width

Image width

The value is an even number within the range of 128–1920.


Int height

Image height

The value is an even number within the range of 128–1920.


Int coding_type

Video encoding protocols: H.265 main level (0), H.264 baseline level (1), H.264 main level(2), and H.264 high level (3)

0~3
0: H.265 main level1: H.264 baseline level2: H.264 main level3: H.264 high level


Int YUV_store_type

YUV image storage format

The value is 0 or 1.
0: YUV420 semi-planar1: YVU420 semi-planar


char* input_data

Address of the input image data

The value cannot be null.


Int input_data_size

Size of the input image data

The value is a positive number.


shared_ptr output_data_queue

Address for output encoded stream

The buffer needs to be configured. This parameter is a smart pointer transferred into the DVPP, used for the caller to allocate the output buffer.
Mandatory





Output Parameter: venc_out_msg
None. The output is read based on the value of output_data_queue  in venc_in_msg.
Calling Example
void TEST_3() //venc demo
{
    int read_file_size;
    int unit_file_size;
    FILE *fp = fopen(in_file_name, "rb");
    if (fp == NULL) {
        printf("open file: %s failed.\n", in_file_name);
        return;
    }
    printf("open yuv success \n");
    fseek(fp, 0L, SEEK_END);
    int file_size = ftell(fp);
    fseek(fp, 0L, SEEK_SET);

    venc_in_msg venc_msg;
    venc_msg.width = gWidth;
    venc_msg.height = gHigh;
    venc_msg.coding_type = gFormat;
    venc_msg.YUV_store_type = gBitwidth;
    venc_msg.output_data_queue = make_shared();
    unit_file_size = gWidth * gHigh * 3 / 2 * MAX_FRAME_NUM_VENC; // The size of a single file is 16 frames.
    dvppapi_ctl_msg dvppApiCtlMsg;
    dvppApiCtlMsg.in = (void *)(&venc_msg);
    dvppApiCtlMsg.in_size = sizeof(venc_in_msg);
    IDVPPAPI *pidvppapi = NULL;
    CreateDvppApi(pidvppapi);
    char out_filename[] = "venc.bin";
    FILE *outputBufferFile;
    outputBufferFile = fopen (out_filename, "wb+");

    do{
       read_file_size = file_size>unit_file_size? unit_file_size:file_size; // The size of the file to be read each time cannot exceed 16 frames.
        venc_msg.input_data = (char *)malloc(read_file_size);
        int read_len = fread(venc_msg.input_data, 1, read_file_size, fp);
        printf("file size is %d,read len is %d.\n", read_file_size, read_len);
        venc_msg.input_data_size = read_len;        

        if (pidvppapi != NULL) {
            if (DvppCtl(pidvppapi, DVPP_CTL_VENC_PROC, &dvppApiCtlMsg) != 0) {
                printf("call dvppctl process faild!\n");
                DestroyDvppApi(pidvppapi);
                fclose(fp);
                fclose(outputBufferFile);
                return;
            }
            if (venc_msg.output_data_queue->getBufferSize() > 100) {// This is used to ensure that the encoding result does not contain only the header information.
                char* out_buf = venc_msg.output_data_queue->getBuffer();
                int out_buf_size = venc_msg.output_data_queue->getBufferSize();
                int write_size = fwrite(out_buf, 1, out_buf_size, outputBufferFile);
                fflush(outputBufferFile);               
            } else {
                printf("venc output data is too small : %d \n", venc_msg.output_data_queue->getBufferSize());
            }

        } else {
            printf("pidvppapi is null!\n");
        }

        if (venc_msg.input_data != NULL) {
            free(venc_msg.input_data);
            venc_msg.input_data = NULL;
        }

        file_size = file_size - unit_file_size;
    } while (file_size > 0);

    DestroyDvppApi(pidvppapi);
    fclose(outputBufferFile);
    fclose(fp);
    return;
}
